Recommendations:
We recommended and Management agreed that the:
Municipal Inventory Committee conduct a physical count of inventory items per type and report the same, with corresponding unit values, in the Report on the Physical Count of Inventories, using the form prescribed by the NGAS Manual for LGUs, and submit to the Auditor concerned not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively;
Designated GSO strictly observe the policies and procedures provided in the NGAS Manual for record-keeping, monitoring, and reporting of inventories, particularly in the use and maintenance of the prescribed inventory forms and reports such as the Stock Card, Requisition and Issue Slip, and the Report on the Physical Count of Inventories;
Designated GSO take custody of all supplies and materials received and control their release through the use of the Requisition and Issue Slips;
Designated GSO submit to the Municipal Accounting Office the Acceptance and Inspection Report, together with the Delivery Receipt and other supporting documents, after inspection of the supplies and materials received for recording in the Supplies Ledger Cards;
Municipal Accountant maintain Supplier Ledger Cards for the recording of all types of supplies and materials; and
Designated GSO conduct a benchmarking activity on the use of inventory software for supply and property management.
We further recommended and Management also agreed that the Designated General Services Officer, together with the Municipal Accountant, Municipal Treasurer, MSWDO Officer, MHO Officer, MDRRMO Officer, and Municipal Engineer, participate in training and seminars on Property and Supply Management and Property Appraisal and Disposal to be conducted by the Commission on Audit, Regional Office XI, within the Calendar Year 2025.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the:

1. Municipal Treasurer and other officials concerned to undertake effective, efficient, and aggressive tax collection strategies to improve collection. Prepare and serve NDs for all delinquent RPUs, prioritize those which are more than 10 years delinquent. If possible, coordinate with other offices that are regularly conducting field inspections, to help them in the distribution of NDs;

2. Municipal Assessor to review the assessment rolls as it appears that several RPUs under the Republic of the Philippines was still assessed and computed with tax due. Coordinate with the Provincial Assessor on correcting the said records in the ETRACS;

3. Municipal Treasurer to conduct dialogue with the owners of the RPUs under CARP, to address concerns on the collection of taxes. If warranted, request the presence of the Provincial Treasurer and Provincial Legal Officer to assist in such undertaking.



4. For the delinquent real property taxes with NDs already served, we recommended the management impose the legal remedies either by administrative auction thru levy on real property or judicial action, following the procedures authorized in the LGC, to enforce collection and to undertake the same expeditiously on a yearly basis to reduce amounts accumulated as receivables for delinquent taxes.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the:  

• GSO to prepare and submit the RSMI in accordance with the GAM and to conduct physical count of inventories taking note of the procedures/guidelines in inventory taking and subsequently submit the RPCI to the MACCO within deadline set;

• MACCO to record the inventory balances based on the submitted RPCI and to conduct periodic review of the subsidiary ledger accounts.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor: 

Secure from the Sangguniang Bayan a resolution confirming its authority to accept donations from various sources for COVID-19 related purposes to rectify the absence of such during the actual receipt; 

Designate in writing, the municipal personnel who shall be responsible in accepting in-kind and cash donations, in behalf of the local government unit; 

Establish an operation manual for relief operations to be incorporated in the MDRRMP taking into consideration the provisions to be included as discussed in this AOM;

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the:

MACCO to strictly comply with the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances. Stop granting cash advances to officials and employees who have previous unliquidated advances;

MHRMO to delete the name of the official or employee from the subsequent payrolls until such time that the travel cash advance has been fully liquidated; and

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the:

MACCO to strictly comply with the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances. Stop granting cash advances to officials and employees who have previous unliquidated advances;

MACCO to send demand letters;

MHRMO to delete the name of the official or employee from the subsequent payrolls until such time that the travel cash advance has been fully liquidated; and

Cause the dissemination of relevant and existing rules and regulations on the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advances to all officials and employees for proper guidance.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor enjoin the:

Municipal Engineer to submit immediately the notice to terminate, verified written report containing the ground/s of termination, request for suspension of work and time extensions as well as its approval to COA;

MEO and BAC to conscientiously abide by the provision/procedures on termination of contract outlined in the RIRR of R.A. No. 9184; 

MEO to devise a catch-up plan to complete the delayed projects to avoid possible wastage of public funds and to strengthen its monitoring activities;

MACCO to strictly and consistently exercise due diligence in checking the completeness and validity of the supporting documents before payment to contractors is approved;

Henceforth, fast track the completion of all projects so that desired benefits are immediately enjoyed by the people.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accounting Office:

To religiously comply with the prescribed period of the submission of the BRS and its supporting documents as prescribed under COA Circular No. 96-011 which is on 15th day following the end of the month;


We further recommend that the Municipal Mayor enjoins the MHRMO to allocate personnel to the MACCO so the latter can discharge its reportorial functions within the prescribed period. Also, the latter shall develop a system that will enable personnel to do accounting duties even in the absence of those assigned for a certain duty/task.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the Ecological Solid Waste Management Board (ESWM Board) the following:

To revisit/review the Municipal Ordinance No. 150 series of 2012 (Ordinance) or the Revised Comprehensive Solid Waste Management Ordinance and to assess its compliance to its own enactment;

To coordinate with the Provincial Government of Davao del Norte as to the establishment of sanitary landfill specified in Article VIII on Disposal Facility of the said Ordinance;

To ensure that PPAs in the table above are completed the soonest possible time; and

To fast track the updating of SWMP, submit the same for deliberation and eventual issuance of approved SWMP.

