We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accounting Office:

 To submit immediately to our Office the Bank Reconciliation Statements (BRS) together with the Bank Statements, credit/debit memos and paid checks of the deposit of all the depository accounts maintained by the Municipality for the periods of July to December 2017;

To submit immediately to our Office the Bank Reconciliation Statements (BRS) together with the Bank Statements, credit/debit memos and paid checks of the bank account with DBP under Account No. 0916-033906-030 for the periods of January to December 2017;

To submit immediately to our Office the Bank Statements, credit/debit memos and paid checks of the bank account with One Network Bank under Account No. 043-25-00573-1 for the months of January to June 2017 and the Bank Reconciliation Statements (BRS) together with the Bank Statements, credit/debit memos and paid checks of the deposit of all the depository accounts maintained by the Municipality for the periods of July to December 2017;

To religiously comply with the prescribed period of the submission of the BRS and its supporting documents as prescribed under COA Circular No. 96-011 which is on 15th day following the end of the month; and

To determine the reason behind the late/non-submission and provide proper and immediate measures to remedy the problem.

We recommended the Municipal Mayor to instruct the Municipal Accounting Office:

To establish a Special Trust Fund solely for LDRRMF and transfer therein the balances under TF-NALGU/BALGU;

To transfer any unexpended balance of LDDRM Funds pertaining to CY 2011 and CY 2012 back to the General Fund;

To maintain a separate subsidiary ledger for the unexpended LDDRM Funds of CY 2013 and CY 2014; and

In the accomplishment of the Report on the Receipt and Utilization of Disaster Risk Reduction and Management, itemized the fund sources and utilization using the suggested format.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require an annual physical inventory of all property, plant and equipment of the local government as of December 31 of each year and designate an inventory committee of three (3) consisting of the representative of the local chief executive as chairman and the general services officer and the supply accountable officer of the department or office concerned, as members.

Likewise, we recommended that:

The Audit Team or its representative shall be invited to witness the conduct of the annual inventory;

The Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) shall be accomplished by the inventory committee by type of property, plant and equipment;

The RPCPPE shall be certified correct by the inventory committee and attested by the Audit Team or its representative; and

The General Services Office and the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the resulting balances of the property, plant and equipment per RPCPPE and the year-end financial statements.

To eliminate the above cycle of obvious violations concerning the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances, we recommended that the Local Chief Executive and the ICO-Municipal Accounting Office take the following measures:

All prior year cash advances should be liquidated immediately;

No cash advances should be given to accountable officers with existing unliquidated cash advances;

Cash advances shall be granted to the officers or employees who will actually utilize the funds for their activities provided these officers shall be duly bonded; and

Rules in the granting, utilization, and liquidation of cash advances as contained in COA Circular No. 97-002 should be strictly adhered to.

The Municipal Accountant should strictly observe the perpetual inventory method of accounting for inventories as provided for under the NGAS Manual for LGUs. 

Likewise, the Supply Officer should undertake the following courses of action:

Maintain stock cards for control and monitoring purposes; 


Require the requisitioning office to prepare Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS) every time stocks are withdrawn from the stock room;

Summarize weekly the RIS in the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) and submit the same to the Accounting Office for recognition of the used inventories and proper classification in the books of accounts; and

Prepare the RPCI for submission to the Auditor not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year.

We recommended the following courses of action:

The constituted Inventory Committee shall determine the conditions of all properties of the municipality by conducting physical counts and submit the Report on Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE). It shall determine the existence and condition of the asset, serviceability of un-serviceability. Segregate unserviceable properties and still usable but no longer utilized in operation from one serviceable/unutilized property;

The Accountant should be directed to set up depreciation expenses for all depreciable items, the necessary Journal entry Voucher to transfer Public Infrastructures Project to their respective Registries and thereafter prepare the Summary of Public Infrastructure based on the registries. Copies of the same shall be submitted annually along with the financial reports as prescribed;

The Accountant shall cause the preparation of the necessary Journal Entry Voucher to transfer Public Infrastructure Project to their respective Registries and thereafter prepare the Summary of Public Infrastructure based on the registries. Copies of the same shall be submitted annually along with the Financial Reports as prescribed;


Require the concerned implementing department to submit a report of all accounts and cause the transfer of these projects to the respective Registries; and



Conduct reconciliation of the RPCPPE prepared by the Inventory committee with the records of the Accounting before the same be submitted to the COA.

To eliminate the above cycle of obvious violations concerning the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances, we recommended that the Local Chief Executive and the ICO-Municipal Accounting Office take the following measures:

Direct all accountable officers with outstanding cash advances for travel and special purposes to settle and liquidate immediately their outstanding cash advances;
If after 30 days, no settlement or liquidation is made, order the withholding of any money due the accountable officers;
No cash advance should be granted to accountable officers with existing cash advances;
Except for the Intelligence Fund, elective officials should only be granted cash advances for their travelling expenses;
Process cash advances with complete supporting documents only; 
Procure authorized meals and snacks in accordance with RA No. 9184; and 
Transfer the cash advances of separated/deceased employees to the “Other Receivables” account.

